Using the golden rule also works well (and in many different ways) for proving the absorption laws — the first one is particularly brief, starting with the golden rule as definition of conjunction:

[10]
Theorem (3.43) (3.43a) “Absorption”: p ∧ (p ∨ q) ≡ p
Proof:
    p ∧ (p ∨ q)
  =⟨ “Definition of ∧”⟩
    p ≡ ((p ∨ q) ≡ p ∨ (p ∨ q)) 
  =⟨ “Associativity of ∨” ⟩
    p ≡ ((p ∨ q) ≡ (p ∨ p) ∨ q) 
  =⟨ “Idempotency of ∨”⟩
    p ≡ ((p ∨ q) ≡ (p ∨ q))
  =⟨ “Identity of ≡” ⟩
    p

[11]
Theorem (3.43) (3.43b) “Absorption”: p ∨ (p ∧ q) ≡ p
Proof:
    p ∨ (p ∧ q)
  =⟨ “Definition of ∧” ⟩
    p ∨ (p ≡ (q ≡ p ∨ q))
  =⟨ “Distributivity of ∨ over ≡”⟩
    (p ∨ p) ≡ (p ∨ (q ≡ p ∨ q))
  =⟨ “Idempotency of ∨”⟩
    p ≡ (p ∨ (q ≡ p ∨ q))
  =⟨ “Distributivity of ∨ over ≡”⟩
    p ≡ (p ∨ q) ≡ (p ∨ p ∨ q)
  =⟨ “Idempotency of ∨”⟩
    p ≡ (p ∨ q) ≡ (p ∨ q)
  =⟨ “Identity of ≡”⟩
    p

